This paper is about a software framework for controlling a humanoid robot, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also discusses the use of multi-threading and parameter binding, which are relevant to systems and control (cs.SY). The use of plugins and an extensible set of transport protocols suggests a focus on software engineering (cs.MA). The paper also mentions a product disassembly task, which could involve computer vision (cs.CV) for object recognition and localization. Finally, the use of a torque-controlled humanoid robot suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) for developing control policies.
